Phase 1: Applied Generative AI & API Integration
Setup IBM Bob on your machine
Setup Github Copilot on Visual Studio code
Understand how to consume LLMs via APIs (OpenAI, Anthropic, Google Vertex AI). [The Project: Write a simple Python script (or use a tool like Postman) that takes a server log file, sends it to an LLM API, and asks the LLM to identify the root cause of an error.]
Learn about prompting techniques, system prompts, context windows, and temperature settings.

Phase 2: RAG and Vector Databases
Giving AI an enterprise memory. LLMs only know what they were trained on. To make them useful for a company, you have to connect them to private data. This is called Retrieval-Augmented Generation (RAG).
Learn how vector databases work (Pinecone, Weaviate, or pgvector). Learn an orchestration framework like LangChain or LlamaIndex, which handles the complex flow of taking a user query, searching the database, and sending the results to the LLM.
The Project: Build a chatbot that can answer questions based strictly on your company's internal Confluence wiki or technical documentation.

Phase 3: AI Agents and Tool Calling
Learn how to build agentic workflows. Instead of just asking an LLM a question, you give it access to tools (like a Python REPL, a GitHub API, or a Kubernetes command line).
The Project: Build an AI agent that takes a natural language prompt ("Restart the failing pod in the staging namespace"), translates it to a kubectl command, executes it, and confirms the status.

Phase 4: AI Platform Infrastructure (LLMOps)
Running open-source models locally or within secure enterprise boundaries, rather than relying on external APIs.
Learn how to deploy and scale inference servers (like vLLM or Triton Inference Server) on Kubernetes. Understand how to manage GPU scheduling and optimize model weights.
The Project: Deploy an open-source model (like Llama 3) onto your Kubernetes cluster and expose it as a secure internal service via Consul.

