ML Concepts/Terminology:-
Training vs inference, model artifacts, checkpoints
What a model registry is, versioning, drift, retraining triggers
Evaluation metrics at a conceptual level (accuracy, precision/recall, perplexity for LLMs)

LLM Concepts:-
Transformer architecture — conceptual only
Context windows, tokens, embeddings (you'll be managing infra around these — cost, latency, memory)
Fine-tuning vs RAG vs prompt engineering — know when each is used, since you'll be asked to support all three

MLOPS Concepts:-
ML pipeline stages: data ingestion → training → validation → deployment → monitoring
Tools: MLflow (experiment tracking/model registry), Kubeflow, Airflow/Dagster for pipelines
Model serving: TorchServe, Triton Inference Server, KServe
Containerization/orchestration for ML workloads (you likely know K8s already — now apply it to GPU scheduling, model serving patterns)
Feature stores (Feast, Tecton) — conceptually

LLMOPS Concepts:-
LLM serving: vLLM, TGI (Text Generation Inference), Ollama for local
Vector databases: Pinecone, Weaviate, Chroma, pgvector — deployment/scaling, not just usage
RAG pipeline infra: chunking strategies, embedding pipelines, retrieval latency
Prompt/version management: prompt registries, A/B testing prompts
LLM observability: LangSmith, Langfuse, Arize — tracing agent calls, token usage, cost tracking
Guardrails/safety: rate limiting, PII filtering, content moderation layers
Agent orchestration at scale: MCP servers, tool-calling infra, multi-agent systems in production

Cost & Performance Engineering Concepts:-
This is a huge, underrated part of LLMOps that plays directly to IT-ops instincts:
Token cost optimization, caching strategies (prompt caching, semantic caching)
GPU utilization, batching, quantization basics (why/when you'd quantize a model)
Latency vs throughput tradeoffs for real-time vs batch inference
